<h2>Example 1</h2>
<p>Take a look at the following graph =E2=88=92</p>
<p><img src=3D"https://www.tutorialspoint.com/graph_theory/images/undirecte=
d_graph.jpg" alt=3D"Undirected Graph" class=3D"fr-fic fr-dii" width=3D"261"=
 height=3D"327"></p>
<p>In the above Undirected Graph,</p>
<ul class=3D"list">
  <li>
    <p>deg(a) =3D 2, as there are 2 edges meeting at vertex 'a'.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>deg(b) =3D 3, as there are 3 edges meeting at vertex 'b'.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>deg(c) =3D 1, as there is 1 edge formed at vertex 'c'</p>
    <p style=3D"padding-left:5%;">So 'c' is a <strong>pendent vertex</stron=
g>.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>deg(d) =3D 2, as there are 2 edges meeting at vertex 'd'.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>deg(e) =3D 0, as there are 0 edges formed at vertex 'e'.</p>
    <p style=3D"padding-left:5%;">So 'e' is an <strong>isolated vertex</str=
ong>.</p>
  </li>
</ul>
<h2>Example 2</h2>
<p>Take a look at the following graph =E2=88=92</p>
<p><img src=3D"https://www.tutorialspoint.com/graph_theory/images/undirecte=
d_graph1.jpg" alt=3D"Undirected Graph 1" class=3D"fr-fic fr-dii" width=3D"2=
08" height=3D"190"></p>
<p>In the above graph,</p>
<p style=3D"padding-left:20px;">deg(a) =3D 2, deg(b) =3D 2, deg(c) =3D 2, d=
eg(d) =3D 2, and deg(e) =3D 0.</p>
<p>The vertex 'e' is an isolated vertex. The graph does not have any penden=
t vertex.</p>
<h2>Degree of Vertex in a Directed Graph</h2>
<p>In a directed graph, each vertex has an <strong>indegree</strong> and an=
 <strong>outdegree</strong>.</p>
<h2>Indegree of a Graph</h2>
<ul class=3D"list">
  <li>
    <p>Indegree of vertex V is the number of edges which are coming into th=
e vertex V.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Notation</strong> =E2=88=92 deg<sup>=E2=88=92</sup>(V).</p>
  </li>
</ul>
<h2>Outdegree of a Graph</h2>
<ul class=3D"list">
  <li>
    <p>Outdegree of vertex V is the number of edges which are going out fro=
m the vertex V.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Notation</strong> =E2=88=92 deg<sup>+</sup>(V).</p>
  </li>
</ul>
<p>Consider the following examples.</p>
<h2>Example 1</h2>
<p>Take a look at the following directed graph. Vertex 'a' has two edges, '=
ad' and 'ab', which are going outwards. Hence its outdegree is 2. Similarly=
, there is an edge 'ga', coming towards vertex 'a'. Hence the indegree of '=
a' is 1.</p>
<p><img src=3D"https://www.tutorialspoint.com/graph_theory/images/directed_=
graph.jpg" alt=3D"Directed Graph" class=3D"fr-fic fr-dii" width=3D"469" hei=
ght=3D"341"></p>
<p>The indegree and outdegree of other vertices are shown in the following =
table =E2=88=92</p>
<table class=3D"table table-bordered">
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th style=3D"text-align:center;">Vertex</th>
      <th style=3D"text-align:center;">Indegree</th>
      <th style=3D"text-align:center;">Outdegree</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
      <td>a</td>
      <td>1</td>
      <td>2</td>
    </tr>
    <tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
      <td>b</td>
      <td>2</td>
      <td>0</td>
    </tr>
    <tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
      <td>c</td>
      <td>2</td>
      <td>1</td>
    </tr>
    <tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
      <td>d</td>
      <td>1</td>
      <td>1</td>
    </tr>
    <tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
      <td>e</td>
      <td>1</td>
      <td>1</td>
    </tr>
    <tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
      <td>f</td>
      <td>1</td>
      <td>1</td>
    </tr>
    <tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
      <td>g</td>
      <td>0</td>
      <td>2</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
<h2>Example 2</h2>
<p>Take a look at the following directed graph. Vertex 'a' has an edge 'ae'=
 going outwards from vertex 'a'. Hence its outdegree is 1. Similarly, the g=
raph has an edge 'ba' coming towards vertex 'a'. Hence the indegree of 'a' =
is 1.</p>
<p><img src=3D"https://www.tutorialspoint.com/graph_theory/images/directed_=
